  <h1>Lee Wilkers</h1>
  <p class="gwern-email"><a href="mailto:lee@leewilkers.com">lee@leewilkers.com</a></p>

  <p>
    <em>realist management</em><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Managing what is rather than what should be. <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Mintzberg+The+Nature+of+Managerial+Work+1973" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Mintzberg, <em>The Nature of Managerial Work</em>, 1973.</a></cite> <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Brunsson+Irrationality+of+Action+Journal+of+Management+Studies+1982" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Brunsson, &ldquo;The Irrationality of Action,&rdquo; <em>J Mgmt Stud</em>, 1982.</a></cite> <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Suchman+Plans+and+Situated+Actions+1987" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Suchman, <em>Plans and Situated Actions</em>, 1987.</a></cite> <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Weick+Sensemaking+in+Organizations+1995" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Weick, <em>Sensemaking in Organizations</em>, 1995.</a></cite></span></span>,
    <em>generative friction</em><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Treating tensions and disagreements as information &ndash; the gaps between what people and organizations say and what they do, between what they do and what they want, and between what they want and what they get asked about. <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Hirschman+Exit+Voice+and+Loyalty+1970" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Hirschman, <em>Exit, Voice, and Loyalty</em>, 1970.</a></cite> <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Argyris+Schon+Organizational+Learning+1978" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Argyris &amp; Sch&ouml;n, <em>Organizational Learning</em>, 1978.</a></cite></span></span>,
    <em>strategic unplanning</em><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">For VUCA-shaped problems &ndash; volatility, uncertainty, complexity, ambiguity &ndash; recognizing when the structure defeats planning. Short experiments take the place of plans until the problem&rsquo;s shape comes into view. <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Bennis+Nanus+Leaders+Strategies+for+Taking+Charge+1985" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Bennis &amp; Nanus, <em>Leaders</em>, 1985.</a></cite> <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Bennett+Lemoine+What+VUCA+Really+Means+for+You+HBR+2014" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Bennett &amp; Lemoine, &ldquo;What VUCA Really Means,&rdquo; <em>HBR</em>, 2014.</a></cite> <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Mintzberg+Crafting+Strategy+Harvard+Business+Review+1987" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Mintzberg, &ldquo;Crafting Strategy,&rdquo; <em>HBR</em>, 1987.</a></cite> <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Scott+Seeing+Like+a+State+1998" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Scott, <em>Seeing Like a State</em>, 1998.</a></cite> <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Stanley+Lehman+Why+Greatness+Cannot+Be+Planned+2015" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Stanley &amp; Lehman, <em>Why Greatness Cannot Be Planned</em>, 2015.</a></cite></span></span>,
    <em>human infrastructure</em><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">The people, relationships, and tacit work that hold a program together. <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=King+Kolopack+Merritt+Lavery+Community+engagement+human+infrastructure+global+health+research+BMC+Medical+Ethics+2014" rel="noopener" target="_blank">King, Kolopack, Merritt &amp; Lavery, &ldquo;Community engagement and the human infrastructure of global health research,&rdquo; <em>BMC Med Ethics</em>, 2014.</a></cite> <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Svensson+Humane+Infrastructures+MIT+Press+2025" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Svensson, <em>Humane Infrastructures</em>, 2025.</a></cite> <cite><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Simone+People+as+Infrastructure+Public+Culture+2004" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Simone, &ldquo;People as Infrastructure,&rdquo; <em>Public Culture</em>, 2004.</a></cite></span></span>
  </p>
  <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; opacity: 0.7;">Health / Science / Policy / Public interest</p>

  <h2>about</h2>
  <p>Hi, I&rsquo;m Lee &ndash; an independent consultant in Atlanta<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">The &ldquo;global health capital&rdquo; of the world &ndash; I&rsquo;ve worked with most major institutions in the area. <em>AKA</em>: city in a forest, hollywood of the south, the A, Hotlanta.<br><em>AUTBKA</em>: Terminus, 1830s &ndash; southern endpoint of the Western &amp; Atlantic Railroad.</span></span>, by way of the DC area<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">The data center capital of the world. DC stands for data center now if you didn&rsquo;t know.</span></span> &ndash; closer to cattle than the Capitol.</p>
  <p>Most of my work has been in and around public health and global health ethics, with formative detours through ecology (complex adaptive systems) and hospitality (complex adaptive services).</p>
  <p>I studied ecology along the James River at Virginia Commonwealth University in Richmond. Then, I spent some time chopping vegetables, washing dishes, and learning what makes customers happy. After that, I got an MPH at Emory&rsquo;s Rollins School of Public Health in Atlanta. I worked at Rollins&rsquo; Global Health department for 7 years before moving next door to the Task Force for Global Health.</p>

  <h2>what i do now</h2>
  <p>Most programs and institutions sit on <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosntds/article?id=10.1371/journal.pntd.0008318" rel="noopener">deep reserves of latent knowledge</a> in the people closest to the work. The reserves hold capacities, potential, and interests that are non-obvious, tacit, and rarely show up in formal channels. For a decade+ I&rsquo;ve helped organizations understand and design for those reserves.</p>

